### Issues in the code

```js
function isValidURL(str) {
  const pattern = new RegExp('^https?:\/\/[^\s]+$');
  return pattern.test(str);
}
```

## 1. Incorrect escaping in the regex string

This is the biggest bug.

Inside a JavaScript string, `\s` is not preserved as a regex whitespace escape unless the backslash is escaped.

```js
'[^\s]'
```

effectively becomes:

```js
'[^s]'
```

So your regex is closer to:

```js
/^https?:\/\/[^s]+$/
```

That means it rejects URLs containing the letter `s`, but allows whitespace, newlines, tabs, etc.

### Example problem

```js
isValidURL("http://example.com") // true
isValidURL("https://example.com") // false because "https" contains s
isValidURL("http://evil.com\nHeader: injected") // may pass
```

### Fix

Use a regex literal:

```js
function isValidURL(str) {
  return /^https?:\/\/\S+$/.test(str);
}
```

Or properly escape backslashes in the `RegExp` constructor:

```js
function isValidURL(str) {
  const pattern = new RegExp('^https?:\\/\\/\\S+$');
  return pattern.test(str);
}
```

But a regex literal is clearer here.

---

## 2. The validation is too permissive

Even with the escaping fixed, this regex accepts many strings that are not valid URLs.

Examples that may pass:

```js
"http://."
"http://?"
"http://<script>"
"http://example.com:badport"
"http://user:pass@example.com"
"http://localhost"
"http://127.0.0.1/admin"
```

The pattern only checks:

- starts with `http://` or `https://`
- followed by one or more non-whitespace characters

That is not enough for reliable URL validation.

---

## 3. Potential security issue if used before fetching URLs

If this function is used to validate user-provided URLs before making server-side requests, it may allow SSRF-style inputs:

```js
http://localhost:3000
http://127.0.0.1
http://169.254.169.254
http://10.0.0.1
http://[::1]
```

These can target internal services, cloud metadata endpoints, or private networks.

### Fix

If the URL will be fetched by your server, you need additional protections:

- reject private IP ranges
- reject localhost
- reject link-local addresses
- resolve DNS and validate the resolved IP
- repeat validation after redirects
- consider DNS rebinding risks
- optionally restrict to an allowlist of domains

---

## 4. No type check

`pattern.test(str)` coerces non-strings to strings.

Examples:

```js
isValidURL(null)      // tests "null"
isValidURL(123)       // tests "123"
isValidURL({})        // tests "[object Object]"
```

That may not be what you want.

### Fix

```js
function isValidURL(str) {
  if (typeof str !== 'string') return false;
  return /^https?:\/\/\S+$/.test(str);
}
```

---

## 5. Recreates the regex every call

This is minor, but the function constructs a new `RegExp` each time it is called.

Better:

```js
const HTTP_URL_PATTERN = /^https?:\/\/\S+$/;

function isValidURL(str) {
  return typeof str === 'string' && HTTP_URL_PATTERN.test(str);
}
```

---

# Recommended approach: use the `URL` constructor

For most cases, prefer the built-in URL parser instead of a custom regex.

```js
function isValidURL(value) {
  if (typeof value !== 'string') return false;

  try {
    const url = new URL(value);

    return (
      url.protocol === 'http:' ||
      url.protocol === 'https:'
    ) && Boolean(url.hostname);
  } catch {
    return false;
  }
}
```

This correctly rejects many malformed URLs and gives you structured access to the protocol, hostname, port, path, etc.

---

## More restrictive version

If you do not want credentials, local hosts, or non-standard ports:

```js
function isValidPublicHttpURL(value) {
  if (typeof value !== 'string') return false;

  let url;

  try {
    url = new URL(value);
  } catch {
    return false;
  }

  if (url.protocol !== 'http:' && url.protocol !== 'https:') {
    return false;
  }

  if (!url.hostname) {
    return false;
  }

  // Reject credentials like http://user:pass@example.com
  if (url.username || url.password) {
    return false;
  }

  // Optional: reject localhost-style hosts
  const hostname = url.hostname.toLowerCase();

  if (
    hostname === 'localhost' ||
    hostname.endsWith('.localhost') ||
    hostname === '127.0.0.1' ||
    hostname === '::1'
  ) {
    return false;
  }

  return true;
}
```

For true SSRF protection, this is still not enough because you also need DNS resolution and IP range checks.

---

# Minimal fix

If you only want to fix the immediate bug:

```js
function isValidURL(str) {
  return typeof str === 'string' && /^https?:\/\/\S+$/.test(str);
}
```

# Better fix

Use `URL`:

```js
function isValidURL(str) {
  if (typeof str !== 'string') return false;

  try {
    const url = new URL(str);
    return url.protocol === 'http:' || url.protocol === 'https:';
  } catch {
    return false;
  }
}
```
